  "prompt": "Can white hairs turn into black?",
  "response": "Hair color is primarily determined by the pigment-producing cells called melanocytes. As people age, these cells may produce less pigment (melanin), leading to grey or white hair. Once hair has turned grey or white due to the reduction or cessation of melanin production, it is generally not possible for those hairs to revert to their original color naturally. \n\nThere are some specific conditions where hair may regain color, such as certain medical treatments or changes in health status. However, these instances are rare. The most common method for changing the color of grey or white hair back to black is through the use of hair dyes.\n\nMoreover, hair health can sometimes be improved through nutrition, stress management, and overall health care, which might have an indirect impact on hair appearance, but not typically in reversing greying.",
